be remaining in physical body till the end, no one else. Neither is this&nb=\r\nsp;to be set as an&nbsp;achieveable target of spiritual progress, or else L=\r\nahiri Mahasaya and Babaji would have mentioned the same clearly. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;div&gt;=\r\n&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;Vedic method, worshipping the devatas, allows for immortality, thro=\r\nugh Soma devata.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Why did not the Rishi=\r\ns of yore or even Krishna, attain physical immortality till end of the cycl=\r\ne of creation? Because if one is immortal in the physical body, one must su=\r\nrvive in it till the end of creation. Anything less is not exactly physical=\r\n immortality, but only living as long as it is necessary for one to live. C=\r\nhang Dev Maharaj lived for 1400 years, and then gave up his body. He is not=\r\n physically immortal.&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;em&gt;No one can attain liberation in Phys=\r\nical body, unless one divinizes it - Kriya and Jnana are not a substitute t=\r\no Iccha shakti.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;Divinizing of the body=\r\n may not necessarily be physical immortality at all. It is merely removing =\r\nimpurities such that a higher consciousness can pervade throughout. &lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p=\r\n&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;-Regards&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;&nbsp; Rajarshi&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;div&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;\n&lt;div&gt;&lt;=\r\nem&gt;&lt;strong&gt;\n&lt;div class=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=3D&quot;font-size: 10pt=\r\n; color: navy; font-family: Verdana;&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=3D&quot;#000000&quot; face=3D&quot;Times=\r\n New Roman&quot; size=3D&quot;3&quot;&gt;&quot;Between me and You, there is only me. \n&lt;/font&gt;&lt;p cl=\r\nass=3D&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;&lt;font color=3D&quot;#000000&quot; face=3D&quot;Times New Roman&quot; size=3D&quot;=\r\n3&quot;&gt;Take away the me, so only You remain&quot; 